{{Infobox organization | native_name = شبكة رصد الاخبارية | native_name_lang = ar | named_after = | image = | image_size = | alt = <!-- see [[WP:ALT]] --> | caption = | abbreviation = RNN | motto = "From the people to the people" | formation = <!-- or: | established = --> <!--e.g. use {{start date and age|YYYY|MM|DD}}--> | founder = <!-- or: | founders = --> | founding_location = | type = [[Digital journalism]] collective | status = <!-- Organization's legal status and/or description (company, charity, foundation, etc) --> | location = [[Egypt]] | region = [[North Africa]], [[Middle East]] | services = | membership = <!-- Usually the number of members --> | membership_year = <!-- Year to which membership number/data apply --> | language = Arabic | website = {{url|www.rassd.com/}} }}
'''Rassd News Network''', also known by its initials of '''RNN''' (Arabic: شبكة رصد الاخبارية), is an [[alternative media]] network based in [[Cairo]], [[Egypt]]. RNN was launched as a [[Facebook]]-based news source launched on January 25, 2011. It quickly advanced to become a primary contributor of [[2011 Egyptian revolution|Egyptian revolution]]-related news that year. Applying the motto "From the people to the people," the [[Citizen journalism|citizen journalists]] who created RNN have since added a [[Twitter]] feed and launched an independent website dedicated to short news stories favored by an [[Internet|online]] audience.<ref name="Solayman_09-2011">{{cite web |url=http://emajmagazine.com/2011/09/13/egypts-revolution-media-a-question-of-credibility/ |title=Egypt's Revolution Media: A Question of Credibility |last=Solayman |first=Hanan |date=13 September 2011 |publisher=EMAJ Magazine |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131202223211/http://emajmagazine.com/2011/09/13/egypts-revolution-media-a-question-of-credibility/ |archive-date=2013-12-02 |accessdate=6 November 2011}}</ref>
RNN is an organized citizen news network with four working committees; one for editing the news, another to support the correspondents covering Egypt, a third for managing the multimedia feeds and a fourth for staff functions such as development, training and public relations. RNN's Arabic name, Rassd, is an acronym that stands for Rakeb (observe), Sawwer (record) and Dawwen (blog). RNN created a [[Ustream]] channel on January 27, 2011, and a YouTube account a month later.
The success of RNN and its new [[social media]] model is evidenced in its recent local network expansion into [[Libya]], [[Morocco]], [[Syria]], [[Jerusalem]] and [[Turkey]].<ref name="Solayman_09-2011"/> Even so, one media scholar in the US (commenting in 2011) called the accuracy of RNN's reporting "fairly mediocre".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.pbs.org/mediashift/2011/09/online-journalism-booms-in-egypt-but-not-without-restriction262.html |title=Online Journalism Booms in Egypt, But Not Without Restriction |last=Sistek |first=Hanan |date=19 September 2011 |publisher=PBS |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130210082742/https://www.pbs.org/mediashift/2011/09/online-journalism-booms-in-egypt-but-not-without-restriction262.html |archive-date=2013-02-10 |access-date=6 November 2011}}</ref>
RNN has endured closures of their Facebook profile and YouTube account as part of the attacks from private media, attempting to thwart their work and influence their content.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://dailynewsegypt.com/alternative-media-grows-restructures-industry.html |title=Alternative Media Grows, Restructures Industry |last=Solayman |first=Hanan |website=[[Daily News Egypt]] |accessdate=23 November 2011}}{{dead link|date=February 2018}}</ref>
==Use of RNN's news by international media== RNN has been a global source of Egyptian revolution-related news since its launch. During the early days of the citizen uprisings across the Middle East, major networks such as BBC, Reuters, Al Jazeera and Al Arabiya used some of Rassd's news and photos, and followed the network on Twitter.<ref>{{cite web|last=Cummin|first=H.J.|title=ICFJ Helps Citizen Journalist Create Top-Ranked News Network in ‘Arab Spring’|url=http://www.icfj.org/node/36586|publisher=International Center for Journalists|accessdate=11 November 2011}}</ref> Three days after the [[web portal|online portal]] went live it was [[Streaming media|streaming video]] to [[MSNBC]] through its Facebook page.<ref>{{cite web|last=Cary|first=Mary Kate|title=Egypt Cuts the Internet in the Face of Revolution|url=https://www.usnews.com/opinion/blogs/mary-kate-cary/2011/01/28/egypt-cuts-the-internet-in-the-face-of-revolution|publisher=US News & World Report|accessdate=6 November 2011}}</ref> Then on February 5, 2011, [[Louisville, Kentucky|Louisville]]'s [[NBC]]-affiliate cited RNN, [[Cairo]] when it reported that [[Hosni Mubarak|President Hosni Mubarak]] had stepped down as head of [[List of political parties in Egypt|Egypt's ruling party]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Report: Mubarak Resigns as Head of Egypt's Ruling Party|url=http://www.wave3.com/story/13975907/report-mubarak-reisgns-as-head-of-egypts-ruling-party|publisher=WAVE 3 News|accessdate=6 November 2011}}</ref>
